This year’s nominees were selected to represent the most compelling and empowering stories released in 2022 across broadcasting and streaming media. Nominated in the “Public Service” category, Rising Against Asian Hate: One Day in March, from The WNET Group Exploring Hate reporting initiative, explores the fight against Asian American hate following the March 2021 mass shootings at three spas in Atlanta. FRONTLINE: Michael Flynn’s Holy War asks how Michael Flynn went from being an elite soldier overseas to waging a “spiritual war” in America. It was nominated in the “News” category. For 80+ years, the Peabody Awards have recognized stories that matter as media narratives that defend public interest, encourage empathy, and teach us to expand our understanding of the world today. Out of nearly 1300 entries from television, podcasts/radio and the web in entertainment, news, documentary, arts, children’s/youth, and public service, 60 are chosen as Nominees and 30 are selected as Winners. 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'NJ Spotlight News launched a new multimedia investigative project about the threats and challenges of the Delaware River today. Water’s Edge: Trials and Tributaries of the Delaware River Watershed explores the watershed area from various geographic and environmental angles to assess the overall health and future of one of New Jersey’s most beloved water areas. NJ Spotlight News will roll out content on the project landing page over the next week starting today. Explore it now at NJSpotlightNews.org/Delaware-watershed. Combining in-depth reporting, sweeping video footage, custom art and graphics, the Water’s Edge project explores the Highlands, the Pinelands, the Bayshore and the Camden industrial regions of the river to gauge the health of the water, the threats of climate change and the diversity of the wildlife that call it home. Multimedia features will tell the stories of species native to New Jersey such as the Golden-winged Warbler, Atlantic Sturgeon, Bald Eagle, Saltmarsh Sparrow and Pine Barrens Tree Frog and also explore South Jersey’s famed cranberry bogs. The Water’s Edge project is the result of six months of reporting, video shoots and graphics work by the NJ Spotlight News team. Its goal is to not only tell the river’s current story, but also examine its challenges over the years, those which lie ahead and the possible remedies to keep it and the ecosystem it sustains healthy for generations to come. ©2024 WNET.
